explanation:
For determining whether any statements in OS_cp are provably unreachable you must know the control-flow and side-effect behavior of the following symbols:

- OS_CHECK_POINTER: This is a macro used at the top of the function. It may perform logging, longjmp, abort, or an early return on a NULL pointer. If it always terminates the function for some inputs the rest of the function becomes unreachable; therefore its expansion/semantics are required.

- OS_printf: OS_CHECK_POINTER (or other called functions) can expand to or call OS_printf. While OS_printf normally returns, its implementation (or macros wrapping it in this project) could perform non-local exits in some configurations; inspect to rule out non-local control flow.

- OS_OpenCreate: Sets return_code and initializes file1/file2. Whether it can return values other than OS_SUCCESS (and whether it always/never does) determines whether the subsequent while (return_code == OS_SUCCESS) loop can be entered; it also affects whether the later cleanup (OS_ObjectIdDefined/OS_close) can be reached.

- OS_SUCCESS: The constant compared to return_code. To reason about whether the while loop condition or the if (return_code == OS_SUCCESS) test can ever be true/false you need the value and intended semantics of OS_SUCCESS (and how OS_OpenCreate/other functions use it).

- OS_OBJECT_ID_UNDEFINED: Initial values of file1/file2 are set to this. Combined with the semantics of OS_OpenCreate and OS_ObjectIdDefined it determines whether the cleanup calls (OS_close) are reachable.

- OS_read: Its return-value semantics (e.g., negative for error, zero for EOF, positive bytes-read) are relied upon to break/continue the outer loop and to assign return_code on error. If OS_read has additional non-local behavior the loop structure could be affected.

- OS_write: Its return-value semantics (negative on error) govern the inner writing loop and whether early breaks/assignments to return_code occur; also needed to determine reachability of code following the inner loop.

- OS_ObjectIdDefined: Used to decide whether OS_close is called. If this always evaluates a certain way given the initialization and OS_OpenCreate behavior then the corresponding OS_close call(s) may be unreachable; so its semantics are required.

- OS_close: Its behavior (normal return vs. possible non-local exit) matters for determining reachability of the subsequent return return_code and any code following the close calls.

Note: The UT_Stub_* testing harness symbols seen in the static call graph are part of unit-test instrumentation; they only matter if the test-stub implementations introduce non-local control flow. If present in the project, their implementations should also be checked, but the primary production symbols listed above are required to determine whether any code paths in OS_cp are impossible (unreachable).
